"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61888","Home Office","false","2014-07-07","<p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of people who have upgraded from a standard to <br>a premium service.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Month</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of upgrades</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2014</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2014</p></td><td><p>17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mar 2014</p></td><td><p>117</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr 2014</p></td><td><p>996</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2014</p></td><td><p>1024</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The specific information required is held in application ‘case notes' on <br>Her Majesty's Passport Office systems which cannot be mined through database <br>queries. Data presented here is an estimate for 2014.<br><br>Information on the number of upgrades prior to January 2014 has not been <br>collated centrally.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-07T15:39:41.4068089Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61888/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61888/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-13","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of applicants who have upgraded to a premium service following contact with the Passport Office in each of the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61889","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>Her Majesty's Passport Office's current guideline for returning calls is to do so within 48 hours. Her Majesty's Passport Office gives priority to those with the most immediate travel plans.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-14T16:13:37.0688775Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61889/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61889/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61889/answer/previousversion/2178","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-13","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what target she has set for the time in which applicants should receive a call back from the Passport Office when making enquiries about applications.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61890","Home Office","false","2014-07-01","<p> </p><p>This information is not held in an accessible form by Her Majesty's Passport Office.<br><br>The cost of extracting this data would be disproportionate and so unfortunately <br>I cannot provide you with the information you have requested.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-01T14:56:01.3687828Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61890/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61890/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61890/answer/previousversion/2179","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-06-13","Passports: Kilmarnock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of passport applications submitted by residents of Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency in each month since June 2010; and how many such cases were processed within three weeks of receipt.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","200724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61891","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority received ten applications under the hardship fund in 2013-14, of which four were successful.</p><p> </p><p>People who did not meet the fund's earnings criteria lodged the six remaining applications. The fund is there to support low-paid workers and four of these six people earned too much to be eligible, while the other two lost no income as a result of the injuries they sustained.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2014-06-23T16:51:43.4622659Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61891/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61891/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-13","Criminal Injuries Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications were made to the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority's Hardship Fund in 2013-14; and what proportion of such applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","200718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61892","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-21","<p>Since April 2010 we have cut our overall spend on temporary staff by £35.5m. We only use temporary staff to fill business-critical posts and essential frontline services where they can provide a fast, flexible and efficient way to obtain necessary skills that are not currently available in-house. We will continue to examine our use of contractors and look for further reductions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In responding to each question we have utilised data provided by our contracted supplier of temporary clerical staff and contracted supplier of temporary operational staff. As the data provided has been supplied by two different third parties there is a slight difference in the way that the answer to question 3 and 4 has been presented.</p><p> </p><p>Temporary operational staff relate to Operational Support Grades (OSGs) used within HM Prison Service. We have contracts in place to provide temporary OSGs to fill in gaps in requirements, for building projects or to fill vacancies short term. Temporary OSGs are a very small proportion of our staff complement.</p><p> </p><p>Uniform operational support staff are Operational Support Grades (OSGs).These are uniformed staff who undertake a wide range of duties in prisons, for example operating prison gates, working in security and managing stores areas. They also escort contractors and their vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>1) The following amounts (exclusive of VAT) have been spent on clerical agency staff across -</p><p> </p><p>January 2014 - £2,983,633.14 (5 week period)</p><p>February 2014 - £2,613,023.10 (4 week period)</p><p>March 2014 - £2,591,678.87 (4 week period)</p><p>April 2014 - £2,900,742.70 (5 week period)</p><p>May 2014 - £2,398,053.57 (4 week period)</p><p>June 2014 - £658,700.28 (1 week period)</p><p> </p><p>2) The following amounts (exclusive of VAT) have been spent on uniform operational support staff –</p><p> </p><p>January 2014 - £1,082,247 (5 week period)</p><p>February 2014 - £1,420,329 (4 week period)</p><p>March 2014 - £1,137,834 (4 week period)</p><p>April 2014 - £1,249,908 (4 week period)</p><p>May 2014 - £2,282,468 (5 week period)</p><p> </p><p>The spend for May 2014 also includes the backdated annual pay rise for eligible workers from 1<sup>st</sup> April 2014.</p><p> </p><p>3) The following number of clerical agency staff have been utilised –</p><p> </p><p>January 2014 - 1571 (Average headcount)</p><p>February 2014 - 1634 (Average headcount)</p><p>March 2014 - 1624 (Average headcount)</p><p>April 2014 - 1578 (Average headcount)</p><p>May 2014 - 1644 (Average headcount)</p><p>June 2014 - 1674 (Average headcount)</p><p> </p><p>4) The following number of uniform operational support staff have been utilised –</p><p> </p><p>January 2014 - 697 (Peak worker number)</p><p>February 2014 - 845 (Peak worker number)</p><p>March 2014 - 867 (Peak worker number)</p><p>April 2014 - 853 (Peak worker number)</p><p>May 2014 - 855 (Peak worker number)</p><p>June 2014 - Peak worker number not available yet.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","200709 ; 200710","2014-10-21T16:31:42.1295447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61892/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61892/answer","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61892/answer/previousversion/3227","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-13","Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many agency workers have been employed as cover for uniform operational support staff in each month since January 2014.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61893","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-18","<p /> <p /> <p>The information regarding how many prisons operated on half regime during (a) January, (b) February, (c) March, (d) April and (e) May 2014, is not collated centrally. The term ‘half regime' is not used in prison establishments, and is unlikely to be interpreted consistently. The processes required to collect this data would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-18T12:37:07.4921642Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61893/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61893/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-13","Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisons operated on half regime during (a) January, (b) February, (c) March, (d) April and (e) May 2014.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61894","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-18","<p /> <p /> <p>The Youth Justice Board commissions a distinct secure estate in which children and young people under the age of 18 are placed. Under-18s will only ever be placed in the adult estate in exceptional circumstances, after a thorough risk assessment, and when it is in the best interests of the young person concerned.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of young people aged under-18 years who were authorised to move into the over-18 estate between 2010 and 2013 is set out in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of under-18s moved to over-18 secure estate</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-18T16:31:07.5429325Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61894/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61894/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-13","Youth Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders under the age of 18 were held in the adult secure estate in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012 and (d) 2013.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200713"
