"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61606","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-19","<p>Promoting greater equality of opportunity in the workforce is a matter the Government takes seriously. The Government is actively engaging with leading organisations in the media industry who are working together through the Creative Diversity Network to help address the under-representation of ethnic minorities in that sector. The industry will outline the steps it intends to take at a roundtable event in early July. Equality data monitoring is among a number of issues that will be discussed. In addition, Ofcom has a number of duties relating to equality of opportunity, as set out in the Communications Act 2003. These include requiring all UK licensed radio and television broadcasters' licences to have in place arrangements for promoting equal opportunities in employment on the basis of gender, race and disability, and to review those arrangements with regard to any relevant guidance published by Ofcom.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","200431 ; 200433","2014-06-19T08:45:45.6220628Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61606/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61606/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Mass Media: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what advice or guidance his Department provides to employers in the media industry on equality monitoring.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","200434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61607","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-19","<p>The Government publishes annual statements on special adviser numbers and paybill costs, including severance pay. Information for each financial year going back to 2010/11 is available at the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-october-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-october-2013</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-19T14:35:43.8922432Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61607/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61607/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department has spent on redundancy payments for special advisers since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian Swales","Redcar","Ian Swales","200474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61608","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-17","<p><strong>HMRC data indicates that between January 2007 and March 2013, over 1,200 film productions have claimed £1.3bn of tax relief. </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>According to the Office of National Statistics and the BFI, the film and video production industry generates around 46,000 jobs and film investment is over £1 billion a year.</strong></p><p><strong><br> To support this important sector the Government has modernised film tax relief and extended the relief to animation, high-end television and video games.</strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>The BFI statistics for 2013 show that these reforms are working, with an increase in overall UK film investment, and that the new TV and animation tax reliefs have supported growth in production in the UK. </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-17T16:44:21.2695051Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61608/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61608/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-12","Film: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of (a) the total amount paid out in film tax relief and (b) the resultant benefit to the UK economy as a result of such tax relief since 2007; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","200470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61609","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-19","<p>The Health Surveys for England and Scotland showed a rate of problem gambling of around 0.5% of the adult population, around 200,000 people. The Responsible Gambling Trust expects to distribute £6,292,000 on treatment, education and research in 2014/15 and is funded by the gambling industry and further donations; a full list of funders can be found on their website ( <a href="http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk</a> ). The Government does not collate details of any expenditure by local authorities or the NHS on problem gambling. DCMS Ministers have regular discussions with their Department of Health colleagues on a range of matters.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","200556","2014-06-19T08:43:48.2864096Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61609/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61609/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health on treating gambling addiction.","false","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","200557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61610","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-19","<p>The Health Surveys for England and Scotland showed a rate of problem gambling of around 0.5% of the adult population, around 200,000 people. The Responsible Gambling Trust expects to distribute £6,292,000 on treatment, education and research in 2014/15 and is funded by the gambling industry and further donations; a full list of funders can be found on their website ( <a href="http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk</a> ). The Government does not collate details of any expenditure by local authorities or the NHS on problem gambling. DCMS Ministers have regular discussions with their Department of Health colleagues on a range of matters.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","200557","2014-06-19T08:43:48.1926458Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61610/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61610/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the number of adult gambling addicts in Britain; and what proportion of total funding on addressing gambling addiction has come from (a) the NHS, (b) local authorities and (c) the gambling industry.","false","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","200556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61611","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-17","<p>The independent regulator Ofcom, is responsible for allocating commercial TV and radio licences. Ofcom has received two applications to operate a local TV service in the Maidstone area on the digital terrestrial television (DTT) platform and anticipates making a decision about the award of this licence in the summer.</p><p>The licence to operate the DAB radio multiplex covering Kent was awarded in 2003. The Kent DAB multiplex currently carries the following stations: BBC Radio Kent, Capital, Heart Kent, Kmfm, Smooth Kent, Xfm and Pop Up radio.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-17T10:13:48.5340042Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61611/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61611/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Local Broadcasting: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many local digital service licences have been awarded in Kent and Medway.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","200386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61612","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-17","<p>Government recognises the important role local media plays in communities, and has created the foundations for new local TV services to establish themselves and enrich UK television with quality local news and programming. Ofcom has received applications for a local TV licence in Maidstone, and we expect an award to be made soon. More widely, 25 local TV services have been licensed to date, and further launches will take place over the summer and autumn.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-17T10:14:47.3376754Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61612/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61612/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Local Broadcasting: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to encourage local media and regional broadcasting in Kent and Medway.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","200387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61613","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-19","<p>All parliamentary questions, tabled to the Department for Culture, Media and Sport in the last parliamentary session, received a substantive answer by the time the House prorogued on 14 May 2014.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-06-19T08:44:25.5122628Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61613/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61613/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many parliamentary questions tabled to his Department in the last parliamentary Session did not receive a substantive answer by the time of the 2014 prorogation; and when each such question was first tabled.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","200442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61614","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-06-19","<p>The roundtable on nuisance calls and texts last met on 23 September 2013 and since then we have worked with stakeholders to finalise our Nuisance Calls Action Plan, which was published on 30 March of this year. The next roundtable meeting is being arranged and will be confirmed soon subject to diary commitments.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-06-19T08:46:27.0349642Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61614/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61614/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-12","Direct Selling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the roundtables on nuisance calls and texts met; and when the next roundtable will meet.","false","Biography information for Mike Crockart","Edinburgh West","Mike Crockart","200416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61615","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-18","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-06-18T16:15:44.7520653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61615/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61615/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","AWE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which US establishments were visited by personnel from the Atomic Weapons Establishment under the terms of the US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement in 2013; and how many staff visited each such establishment.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","200408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61616","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>The term rekit is used by the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE) to mean the replacement or modernisation of process plant and /or equipment within an existing facility, including upgrading of building services. The following is a list of major facility rekits that have or are taking place at AWE. There are also a number of more minor rekits underway which are not listed.<br><br>Depleted Uranium Upgrade<br>Beryllium Facility <br>Plutonium Capability Programme (A90)<br>Enriched Uranium Facility (A45)<br>Explosive storage and processing Facility <br>Salts Sustainment<br>Facility for assembly/disassembly of Warhead<br><br>The information relating to individual rekit costs for each facility for the years 2003 to date is not centrally held and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-06-23T15:36:11.1783153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61616/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61616/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","AWE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what facility rekit projects have taken place at the Atomic Weapons Establishment under the scope of the Nuclear Weapons Capability Sustainment Project; and what the cost of each such project was.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","200409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61617","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p>Pegasus is the replacement highly enriched uranium component manufacturing and storage facility, and forms part of the Government's programme of investment in the Atomic Weapons Establishment sites. <br><br>In accordance with normal industry best practice, the project is under regular review to ensure that the facility will meet the Ministry of Defence's requirements while also achieving the optimum balance of performance, cost and schedule. No changes to the approved scope of the project have been made.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-02T15:45:49.837534Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61617/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61617/answer","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61617/answer/previousversion/4722","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","AWE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons a review of the scope of Project Pegasus is being undertaken at the Atomic Weapons Establishment; and what changes he expects to be made to the scope of the project as a result of the review.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","200410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61618","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>One question tabled to the Ministry of Defence in the last Parliamentary session did not receive a substantive reply by the time of the 2014 prorogation.<br><br>The tabling date for this question was 14 March 2014.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T15:36:45.7078726Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61618/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61618/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many parliamentary questions tabled to his Department in the last parliamentary Session did not receive a substantive answer by the time of the 2014 prorogation; and when each such question was first tabled.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","200443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61619","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-18","<p> </p><p>There are no plans for the Ministry of Defence to review the conduct of, nor representation at, Local Liaison Committees relating to Defence nuclear sites. The operation of such committees is a matter for agreement between the individual site operator (the Licensee and/or Authorisee) and the appropriate local authorities.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-06-18T16:02:30.9935855Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61619/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61619/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has for reviewing the conduct of and representation on Local Liaison Committees for defence nuclear sites.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","200398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61620","Ministry of Defence","true","2014-06-23","<p>Between its launch in March 2012 to 31 March 2014, the Army has paid Capita £100.380 million for the Recruiting Partnering Project. The Recruiting Partnering Project remains within the overall agreed cost of £1.360 <ins class="ministerial">billion. </ins><del class="ministerial">million.</del><br /><br />My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Philip Hammond) set out on 14 January 2014 the cost of Capita providing a new Information Technology platform as part of the Recruiting Partnering Project (Official Report: column 716). At the time, these costs were expected to be around £47.7 million directly linked to the change of hosting provision. Since this statement, these costs have reduced to around £42.9 million. <br /><br />As previously stated by the Secretary of State on 14 January, there has been an additional cost of around £1 million per month to run the Capita system. This includes costs for additional manpower.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T16:43:56.43Z","2014-08-01T09:48:10.9953114Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61620/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61620/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61620/answer/previousversion/4680","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will estimate the (a) monthly and (b) total additional cost to date for paying Capita as if it was meeting quantity and quality standards for recruitments in the Recruiting Partnering Project.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","200381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61621","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>The figures used by the NAO in paragraph 11 of their report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, were taken from Future Reserves 2020: The Independent Commission to Review the United Kingdom's Reserve Forces. I refer the hon. Member to paragraph 97. This involved considerable work to develop a Regular: Reserve Cost Comparison Model.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","200573","2014-06-23T16:43:16.6638913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61621/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61621/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page eight, when Ministers in his Department first established that reserves cost around 87 per cent of the cost of regulars when mobilised.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61622","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-08","<p> </p><p>To support the UK's contribution to the NATO ISAF mission in Afghanistan UK military aircraft regularly transit to and from Afghanistan through non Afghan airspace .There has not been any employment of armed UK aircraft outside of the borders of Afghanistan in support of ISAF.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-08T15:45:54.8527482Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61622/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61622/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61622/answer/previousversion/4721","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether UK aircraft have flown outside Afghan airspace in support of NATO International Security Assistance Force missions in Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","200555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61623","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>The figures used by the NAO in paragraph 11 of their report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, were taken from Future Reserves 2020: The Independent Commission to Review the United Kingdom's Reserve Forces. I refer the hon. Member to paragraph 97. This involved considerable work to develop a Regular: Reserve Cost Comparison Model.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","200574","2014-06-23T16:43:16.5857529Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61623/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61623/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page eight, if he will provide a breakdown of the costings used to work out that reserves cost around 87 per cent of the costs of regulars when mobilised.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61624","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Philip Hammond) set out on 14 January 2014 (Official Report, column 716) the cost of Capita providing a new Information Technology platform as part of the Recruiting Partnering Project. At the time, these costs were expected to be around £47.7 million directly linked to the change of hosting provision. Since this statement, the £47.7 million has reduced to £42.9 million. <br><br>As previously stated by the Secretary of State on 14 January, there has been an additional cost of around £1 million per month to run the Capita system. This includes costs for additional manpower. <br><br>The Recruiting Partnering Project remains within the overall agreed cost of £1.360 billion.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","200300","2014-06-24T14:51:44.8611292Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61624/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61624/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61624/answer/previousversion/4717","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page 30, if he will provide a breakdown of the extra £70 million in costs that will be borne by his Department for the decision to revert to a hosting environment provided by Capita as part of the Recruiting Partnering Project.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61625","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>Implementation Orders are used to communicate structural changes within the Army. As at June 2014 over 170 orders have been issued for Army 2020. The Ministry of Defence does not routinely publish details of internal military orders.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-06-24T12:34:49.6130902Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61625/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61625/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page 25, if he will provide details of (a) the 167 implementation orders that his Department has already issued as part of the Army 2020 reforms and (b) any implementation orders which have yet to be issued.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61626","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-18","<p>The Ministry of Defence will respond to the NAO's report in line with Government practice for such reports.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-06-18T16:12:51.1832993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61626/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61626/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department will issue a formal response to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61627","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Statement and paper my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Philip Hammond) placed in the Library of the House on 19 Dec 2013 (Official report, column 124WS).</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T16:46:25.7802556Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61627/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61627/answer","20131219 - WMS Future Reserves 2020[1].doc","20131219 - WMS Future Reserves 2020[1].doc","20131219 Hansard extract ","20131219 Hansard extract ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61627/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will provide details of the current workforce model for the Army Reserve that his Department is using to assess how long it will take to recruit the required number of 30,000 reserves; and when under the current model that target will be met.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61628","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-25","<p>The term “recruitment target” has been interpreted as the 30,000 trained Army Reservists required under Army 2020.<br><br>During the Three Month Exercise, the Ministry Of Defence examined a range of Force Structure options which were assessed as being able to deliver the policy demand specified by the new Defence Planning Assumptions laid out in Strategic Defence and Security Review 2010. As a result of this, a Senior Military Judgement Panel chaired by the Vice Chief of the Defence Staff and including the Assistant Chiefs of the Royal Navy, Army and Royal Air Force concluded that the size of the Regular Army should be 82,500, and the Independent Commission to Review the United Kingdom's Reserve Forces recommended an Army Reserve of 30,000 trained personnel. This was judged to be the optimal size and shape of the Army within available resources.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-25T16:10:50.9194584Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61628/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61628/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61628/answer/previousversion/4720","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what planning data was used to devise his Department's recruitment target for the Army Reserve as part of its Army 2020 reforms.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61629","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-24","<p> </p><p>Following the Strategic Defence and Security Review, a three month exercise was undertaken which examined a range of force structure options which built upon analysis undertaken during the review. These options were then tested for their efficacy against a wide range of scenarios. The options were then assessed by a senior judgement panel, chaired by the Vice Chief of Defence Staff. Included in this panel were the Assistant Chiefs of Staff for the Royal Navy, Army and royal Air Force. The panel took decisions collectively and all members were fully involved and consulted.<br><br>In July 2011 an Independent Commission to Review the UK's Reserve Forces, chaired by my hon. Friend, the member for Canterbury and Whitstable (Julian Brazier) and General Sir Nicholas Houghton, then set a target of 30,000 for a trained Army Reserve. This judgement was reached in the knowledge that the strength of the Territorial Army had been over 70,000 in the 1980s. <br><br>Subsequent work was then undertaken to establish the timescales to build the trained strength of the Army Reserve to 30,000. This was set out in the Written Ministerial Statement and paper placed in the Library of the House by my right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Defence (Philip Hammond) on 19 December 2013 (Official Report, column 124WS).</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-24T14:44:38.9745852Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61629/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61629/answer","Hansard Extract FR2020.doc","Hansard Extract FR2020.doc","Hansard Extract FR2020","Hansard Extract FR2020","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61629/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61629/answer/previousversion/2134","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what preliminary tests his Department conducted to assess whether it was feasible to recruit and train the required number of reserves within the necessary timescale envisaged by the Army 2020 proposals.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61630","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement and paper my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Philip Hammond) placed in the Library of the House on 19 December 2013 (Official report, column 124WS). The hon. Member will be aware that this is a five-year plan and I am confident that the Army will reach this target.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T15:16:18.9094207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61630/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61630/answer","20131219 - Hansard extract on Future Reserves 2020[1].doc","20131219 - Hansard extract on Future Reserves 2020[1].doc","20131219 Hansard extract","20131219 Hansard extract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61630/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page 12, what his Department's response is to the recommendation that it should reassess its targets for recruiting reserves.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61631","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-19","<p> </p><p>I am not able to provide the information requested, since to do so could adversely affect the formulation of future defence policy.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-06-19T16:01:17.1427555Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61631/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61631/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page 17, if he will provide details of the eight options for force structures that his Department considered in 2011, and his Department's estimate of the savings each would have accrued.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61632","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>A number of factors contributed to the problems experienced with the Information Communication Technology hosting environment provided for Capita. <br><br>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Philip Hammond) on 14 January 2014 (Official Report, column 715) to the hon. Member for Gedling (Vernon Coaker).</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T16:46:00.1230277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61632/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61632/answer","20140114 Oral Statement IT Systems.doc","20140114 Oral Statement IT Systems.doc","20140114 Hansard Extract on IT Systems","20140114 Hansard Extract on IT Systems","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61632/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons his Department did not provide supporting ICT infrastructure for Capita's new recruitment software as required under its contractual arrangements with Capita in relation to the Recruiting Partnering Project.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61633","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 21 January 2014 (Official Report, column 111W).</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T16:47:12.6410675Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61633/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61633/answer","20140121 Hansard extract Recruitment doc.doc","20140121 Hansard extract Recruitment doc.doc","20140121 Hansard extract","20140121 Hansard extract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61633/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page 10, which Minister in his Department signed off on the decision not to provide supporting ICT infrastructure for Capita's new recruitment software as part of his Department's contractual arrangements with Capita in relation to the Recruiting Partnering Project.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200576"
