"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61640","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-16","<p>The vast majority - approximately 85% - of the savings referred to in the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, are the direct result of the reduction in the size of the Regular Army from 94,000 to 82,500.<br><br>The remaining savings arise from associated cost reductions, such as the reduced requirement for civilian support.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-16T15:33:51.7693432Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61640/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61640/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61640/answer/previousversion/4719","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014, page five, if he will provide a breakdown of the £5.3 billion savings that reductions in the army would save from 2012-13 to 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200572"
