"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61650","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>Infantry training at Catterick is comprised of the Combat Infantryman's Course, which is a combined phase one and phase two course. For this reason it is not possible to provide the information requested for those who dropped out of training before completing Phase 1. The table shows all those who failed to complete the Combat Infantryman's Course.</p><p>No female recruits undergo infantry training and therefore figures shown relate to males only:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Discharged at ITC (Male)</p></td><td><p>Under 18 on entry (Male)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2006-07</strong></p></td><td><p>950</p></td><td><p>320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2007-08</strong></p></td><td><p>1,090</p></td><td><p>290</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008-09</strong></p></td><td><p>1,060</p></td><td><p>210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p>1,400</p></td><td><p>250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p>840</p></td><td><p>90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p>1,260</p></td><td><p>120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p>910</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>680</p></td><td><p>80</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Figures have been rounded to 10; numbers ending in ‘5' are rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T15:29:56.0235275Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61650/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61650/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) male and (b) female recruits dropped out of training at Catterick Infantry Training Centre before completing Phase 1 in each year since 2006; how many such recruits in each category were aged under 18 when they enlisted; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","200582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61651","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>Infantry training at Catterick is comprised of the Combat Infantryman's Course, which is a combined phase one and phase two course. The table includes all those who commenced the Combat Infantryman's Course.</p><p>No female recruits undergo infantry training and therefore figures relate to males only.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Male</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>3,110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>3,250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>3,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>3,790</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2,320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>3,580</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>3,240</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>1,530</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Figures have been rounded to 10; numbers ending in ‘5' are rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T15:29:26.5701365Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61651/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61651/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) male and (b) female recruits have commenced Phase 1 training at Catterick Infantry Training Centre in each year since 2006; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","200583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61652","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>The National Audit Office made a number of observations and recommendations in their report into Army 2020. The Department will respond to these in due course. Part of the reason the Army has entered a recruitment partnership with Capita is to harness the benefits of an integrated recruiting system to help the Army drive more effective end to end recruiting and training activity. As the Capita IT systems and applications and the Recruitment Partnering Project reaches Full Operating Capability, and can interact with other IT tools available to the Army, we would expect to see these benefits realised.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-23T16:45:32.2911233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61652/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61652/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to rectify the (a) inconsistent understanding of Army staffing requirements, (b) limited use of management information and (c) unsystematic approach to improvement in relation to the Recruiting Partnering Project referred to on pages 36 and 37 of the National Audit Office report, Army 2020, HC 263, published on 11 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","200584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61653","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-23","<p>The Memorandum of Understanding is still undergoing the review process. However, it will cover both the ISAF mission and any future wider NATO missions.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-06-23T15:40:39.6188147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61653/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61653/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 12 September 2013, Official Report, column 798W, on Unmanned Aerial Vehicles, whether changes to the Reaper Agreement pertaining to the UK Reaper Force Squadron have been finalised; and whether this Agreement will remain in force following the cessation of NATO International Security Force missions in Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","200600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61654","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-17","<p>There are no longer any RAF personnel embedded with 432nd Wing of the US Air Force at Creech Airforce base.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-06-17T16:03:07.3315246Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61654/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61654/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-12","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 25 March 2013, Official Report, column 940W, on Unmanned Aerial Vehicles, whether UK personnel at Creech Airforce base will remain embedded following the cessation of NATO International Security Force missions in Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","200599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61655","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-17","<p>Sixteen Parliamentary Questions, all of which were tabled to my Office one day before prorogation in the last Parliamentary Session, did not receive a substantive answer by the time of the 2014 prorogation.</p><p> </p>","Sheffield, Hallam","Mr Nick Clegg",,"2014-06-17T10:52:48.4426426Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61655/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Clegg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61655/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-12","Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, how many parliamentary questions tabled to his Office in the last parliamentary Session did not receive a substantive answer by the time of the 2014 prorogation; and when each such question was first tabled.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","200444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61656","Department for Education","false","2014-06-19","<p>Two parliamentary questions tabled to the Department for Education, PQs 198493 (tabled on 13/5/2014) and 198434 (tabled on 12/5/2014), did not receive substantive answers by the time of prorogation. The questions had reply on dates during prorogation, and therefore could not be answered due to the House's rules regarding notice periods.</p><p> </p><p>As a courtesy, both Members have been sent copies of the answers that they would have received had the Department been permitted to give the answers in the usual way.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-06-19T16:15:37.6292099Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61656/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61656/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many parliamentary questions tabled to his Department in the last parliamentary Session did not receive a substantive answer by the time of the 2014 prorogation; and when each such question was first tabled.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","200445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61657","Department for Education","false","2014-06-19","<p>The Department for Education has received three letters recently on funding sixth forms in rural schools. We recognise the importance of rural schools, many of which are small schools, and the need to maintain access to a local school in rural areas. Often these schools are at the heart of their community.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-19T11:05:22.9700961Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61657/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61657/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Sixth Form Education: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent representations he has received on funding sixth forms in rural schools.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","200419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61658","Department for Education","false","2014-06-17","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-17T11:29:08.0517098Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61658/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61658/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Classroom Assistants: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teaching assistant training posts have been (a) commissioned and (b) filled in in (i) Copeland and (ii) Cumbria in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","200365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61659","Department for Education","false","2014-06-19","<p>There is one school judged to require special measures in Copeland. There are 12 schools in special measures in Cumbria.</p><p> </p><p>Of these 12 schools, nine have received HMI monitoring visits where they have been judged to be either making reasonable progress or their plans are fit for purpose. Two schools are awaiting monitoring visits.</p><p> </p><p>The Interim Executive Board of Walney School has voted to become an academy on 1 September 2014, sponsored by Queen Katherine Academy Trust. The school was granted an Academy Order in April 2014.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-19T12:38:11.733552Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61659/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61659/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61659/answer/previousversion/2133","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the current status is of schools placed in special measures in (a) Copeland and (b) Cumbria; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","200366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61661","Department for Education","false","2014-06-17","<p>Responses to the consultation on further delegation of children's social care functions are currently being considered.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-17T16:32:44.5043963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61661/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61661/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations he has received in support of his proposals to allow further delegation of children's social care functions in order to improve outcomes for children in receipt of child protection services.","false","Biography information for Meg Munn","Sheffield, Heeley","Meg Munn","200384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61662","Department for Education","false","2014-06-17","<p>Responses to the consultation on further delegation of children's social care functions are currently being considered. Local authorities will be able to apply to the Children's Social Care Innovation Programme for support to make use of any new freedoms introduced, and the impact of activities funded through the programme will be robustly evaluated.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-17T16:31:58.5930021Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61662/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61662/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he plans to develop pilot projects of his proposals to allow further delegation of children's social care functions.","false","Biography information for Meg Munn","Sheffield, Heeley","Meg Munn","200385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61663","Department for Education","false","2014-06-19","<p>We have published a more rigorous curriculum for English and mathematics. The new national curriculum sets expectations that match those in the highest-performing education jurisdictions in the world, challenging pupils to realise their potential in an increasingly competitive global market. It increases the level of demand from an early age, with greater emphasis on arithmetic, including learning times tables to 12 x 12 by age 9 and removing calculators from key stage 2 tests in mathematics, and on phonics, grammar and vocabulary development in English. GCSEs in English language and mathematics are also being reformed to be more challenging and give stronger guarantees of literacy and numeracy, with the mathematics GCSE in particular covering more than the current GCSE.</p><p> </p><p>We are confident that our reform to the national curriculum will give teachers greater flexibility and freedom, which will help to raise standards and expectations for all pupils. It has been significantly slimmed down and will free-up teachers to use their professional judgement to provide support that best meets the needs of their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>We have invested in and reformed initial teacher training (ITT) to focus on attracting the very best graduates with the right qualities for teaching into the profession through making more scholarships available; using bursaries to attract more of the most talented graduates in key subjects such as maths and physics and supporting the expansion of the highly-successful Teach First programme. Teach First is now the largest graduate recruiter in any sector in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>In 2013/14, we recruited 96% of the overall number of trainees we set out to recruit and the proportion with first-class or 2:1 degrees has risen 3 percentage points (74%) – a record compared to last year (71%). We have raised the bar for entry into ITT by making skills tests tougher, limiting candidates to two re-sits and making passing the tests in literacy and numeracy a requirement before entering, rather than exiting, ITT.</p><p> </p><p>Sir Andrew Carter has been appointed to lead an independent review about the effectiveness of ITT. As part of this, the review will look at ITT courses for both primary and secondary teaching to consider how well trainees are equipped to become outstanding teachers.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-06-19T16:27:54.2409837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61663/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61663/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Education: Basic Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department has taken to ensure a high standard of teaching in numeracy and literacy.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","200344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61664","Department for Education","false","2014-06-17","<p> </p><p>The independent School Food Plan, published in July 2013, is designed to increase the quality and take-up of school meals in England and ensure that the food available conforms to healthy standards. As part of the School Food Plan, we are introducing new statutory food-based standards for schools in England from January 2015 and funding three organisations to increase take-up in junior and secondary schools.</p><p> </p><p>From September 2014 we are introducing free school meals for every child in reception, year 1 and year 2 in state-funded schools in England, to ensure that every child in those year groups has access to a nutritious lunch. We are targeting infants in order to help establish good eating patterns early. Our intention is that by providing a meal when children start at school, they and their parents will see the benefits of school meals and continue to choose them throughout their education.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-17T15:31:18.2364799Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61664/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61664/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that children at primary and secondary schools have access to a healthy and balanced dinner each day.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","200348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61665","Department for Education","false","2014-06-17","<p>The latest estimate of the proportion of 17-year-olds participating in education is included in “Participation in Education, Training and Employment by 16-18 Year olds in England” Statistical First Release (SFR), which is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/participation-in-education-training-and-employment-by-16-to-18-year-olds-in-england-end-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/participation-in-education-training-and-employment-by-16-to-18-year-olds-in-england-end-2012</a></p><p>This release includes figures reflecting the position at the end of 2012, before raising the participation age (RPA) was implemented. The next release, due on 25 June 2014, will include updated figures for end 2013 which will reflect the first cohort impacted by the implementation of RPA.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-17T11:25:12.7211302Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61665/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61665/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Sixth Form Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the proportion of 17 year olds staying in education (a) before and (b) after the raising of the participation age.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","200516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61666","Department for Education","false","2014-06-18","<p>The Department for Education has not made an assessment of the effect of the current starting age for children entering primary education on the wellbeing and attainment of those born in the summer months.</p><p>However, research[1] carried out by the Department has demonstrated that the age at which tests are taken is the dominant reason for month of birth gaps in educational attainment, and not the age at which children start school; it is simply the fact of being younger when tested that accounts for most of the differences observed. The research reported no evidence of a causal relationship between school entry age and attainment.</p><p>Parents of summer born children who think their child is not ready to start school can request that their child is admitted outside of their normal age group and be admitted to reception year in the September following their fifth birthday. The school's admission authority is responsible for making the decision which must be based on the individual circumstance of each case.</p><p>[1]<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/182664/DFE-RR017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/182664/DFE-RR017.pdf</a></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-06-18T16:32:29.7020611Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61666/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61666/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Primary Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the current starting age for children entering primary education on the wellbeing and attainment of those born in summer months.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","200501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61667","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-19","<p>The Government currently has no plans to introduce a national statutory concession for young people. However, we recognise the importance of affordable and accessible bus services in enabling young people to access education, employment and training and note that, whilst there is no statutory obligation to provide reduced fares to young people, many bus operators and local authorities make discounts available. It is right that local authorities and the bus industry continue to take the lead in improving services for their younger customers, and I encourage them to continue innovating in this area.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-19T12:35:22.8222318Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61667/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61667/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-12","Schools: Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will introduce a concessionary bus fare scheme for 16 to 18 year olds to allow them to pay child fare for their school bus passes.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","200502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61668","Department for Education","false","2014-06-18","<p>The Department does not hold a list of ministerial visits and to compile a list would exceed the cost threshold.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-06-18T16:30:43.1949174Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61668/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61668/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Official Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what visits each of the Ministers in his Department have made since January 2013; and what the purpose of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","200482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61669","Department for Education","false","2014-06-17","<p>The Department has not received any applications for free schools in Copeland. We have received one application from Cumbria within the last two years, which was successful.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-17T12:52:57.0228837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61669/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61669/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-12","Free Schools: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications for free schools have been made in (a) Copeland constituency and (b) Cumbria in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","200533"
